article.headline: No. 14 North Carolina tops Louisville 93-76

images.name: Tar Heels roll past Louisville
images.caption: No. 14 North Carolina cruises to victory behind Joel Berry II's 23 points while Theo Pinson and Luke Mayo each drop 19 in a 96-76 win over Louisville.

article.story: LOUISVILLE, Ky. -- North Carolina got the fast start it sought against Louisville and the No. 14 Tar Heels displayed that energy in numerous areas, giving coach Roy Williams a lot to like -- for the most part. Joel Berry scored 23 points, Luke Maye had 19 with 13 rebounds and North Carolina dominated the boards and second-chance points to beat the Cardinals 93-76 Saturday night for its fifth consecutive victory. The Tar Heels (21-7, 10-5 Atlantic Coast Conference) scored 10 straight points for a 12-3 lead before warming up from long range to eventually build a 19-point cushion before withstanding several Louisville rallies. UNC made eight from behind the arc in the first half alone and 12 of 27 overall in a fast pace that Louisville struggled to keep up with. "We just came out and hit them right in the mouth," said Berry, who made 9 of 20 from the field and 5 of 11 from long range. "They tried to make a run, but as I always say, `the game is all about runs.' But we were up so much we came out and hit them in the mouth so early when they did (rally) it didn't matter." Most impressive for the Tar Heels was doing all this as leading scorer Luke Maye tried to get going offensively. The junior forward had just two points on 1-of-5 shooting in the first half before making 7 of his final 13 attempts. Maye's rebounding offset that slow shooting start, helping the Tar Heels win the glass 44-32 and frequently get timely offensive boards to outscore the Cardinals 22-6 in second-chance points. Though UNC's defense struggled at times, it still held Louisville to just one free throw over the final 3:06. "All in all, we really played well," Williams said. "I didn't like our defense, but I haven't liked our defense all year long. Maybe we'll get it changed before I turn 90. But we made shots and guys made plays." Theo Pinson also scored 19 points, Cameron Johnson 12 and Kenny Williams 11 as North Carolina posted 20 assists for its first win in Louisville against the Cardinals in five tries. Louisville (18-9, 8-6) got within single digits several times but no closer than seven in having its two-game winning streak end. Deng Adel returned from a two-game absence with an ankle injury to score 20 points and Ray Spalding 18 with 12 rebounds. NO WORRIES Maye wasn't bothered by a first half in which his lone basket came late on a tip-in. If anything, that play typified the Tar Heels' hustle and it was just a matter of time before he found his offensive flow. "It wasn't only one play that made it," Maye said. "I was struggling from the beginning. It's not all about me. We were winning, had a good run going." BIG PICTURE North Carolina: Being in the right place at the right time throughout helped the Tar Heels finally break through in Louisville. That's no surprise considering they entered the game outrebounding opponents by a margin of 11.7, and they grabbed 17 offensive boards. Every time Louisville seemed intent on making it a game, they'd answer with a 3 or come up with a rebound and putback to stay safely ahead. They shot 48 percent and broke 90 points for the third time in their current streak. Louisville: The Cardinals' bench dominated 35-9 thanks to Adel, who came off the bench to make 8 of 12 from the field. But they couldn't stop Carolina from getting multiple chances at the start and lost the paint battle 42-38. Most importantly, they missed another chance to get their signature win they've sought all season. "I told Roy if they shot like that it's going to take a heck of a team to beat them," interim coach David Padgett said. "They seemed to counter every one of our runs with a run." UP NEXT North Carolina visits Syracuse on Wednesday night. Louisville visits Duke on Wednesday night in search of its first win at Cameron Indoor Stadium since joining the ACC. --- For more AP college basketball coverage: http://collegebasketball.ap.org and http://twitter.com/AP-Top25

videos.headline: Louisville rejection leads to 3-pointer
videos.description: During a fast-break attempt for UNC, Cameron Johnson goes up for the layup but gets denied by Louisville's Anas Mahmoud. Ray Spalding recovers the block and passes it to Quentin Snider who drains the 3-pointer for the Cardinals.

videos.headline: UNC starts red-hot from deep
videos.description: The Tar Heels start against the Cardinals on fire from the 3-point line, going 5-of-7 from distance.

videos.headline: Louisville's Adel lays it in with flick of the wrist
videos.description: Louisville's Deng Adel drives past UNC defenders and completes a crafty finger-roll layup with a flick of his wrist.

videos.headline: Spalding emphatically denies UNC attempt
videos.description: North Carolina's Cameron Johnson drives to the basket but gets completely denied by Louisville's Ray Spalding.

videos.headline: Louisville's Sutton goes all out for left-handed and-1
videos.description: Louisville's Dwayne Sutton takes the ball from corner-3 territory, drives toward the basket and falls while putting up a left-handed, 2-point attempt which drops.

videos.headline: Berry's no-look pass luckily leads to UNC points
videos.description: North Carolina's Joel Berry II drives to the basket but due to being heavily guarded, decides to pass it backwards which luckily ends up in the hands of teammate Sterling Manley who sinks the easy layup.

videos.headline: UNC's Berry makes up for miss with nasty chase-down block
videos.description: After Joel Berry II missed jumper, Louisville's Deng Adel plays it up to Ray Spalding who goes up for the dunk but gets stuffed by Joel Berry II who sprinted back on defense.

videos.headline: Berry reflects on UNC's team-oriented victory against Louisville
videos.description: Joel Berry II, alongside his "bodyguard" Theo Pinson,  reflects on UNC's ability to share the ball and hit important shots to get their first ever win in Louisville.
